metadata.name: Fifty Windows #11
metadata.description:
"Fifty Windows" is a minimal generative art project that explores thoughts and feelings around the theme of life's choices, by symbolically representing the idea of looking through a window to the other side, where there are all the opportunities and life experiences that we could have missed.

But the other side of the window also represent the idea of a gaze that looks out, where one can explore different life experiences and new paths of growth and fulfillment.

The project is also focused on the idea of perspective, that is allowed by the minimalistic tracts of the artworks, that make you understand that you’re in front of a windows, but you’re never sure if you're looking in or out.

Just like in life, sometimes we may be on one side of the window, feeling like we've missed something, while other times we're living something that others may be regretting.

Life is just a game of perspectives.

- - -

To save artworks at high resolution press "s" in live mode and wait :)

- - -

metadata.name: Echoes of Enough #128
metadata.description:
"Echoes of Enough" is a collection that explores self-worth, acceptance, and validation. The collection presents a visual representation of the struggles, doubts, and triumphs of recognizing our own value. Each piece delves into different aspects of ourselves and how they contribute to this feeling.

The seemingly chaotic yet orderly arrangement of the shapes in this collection reflects the tumultuous nature of the human experience. It speaks to the push and pull of self-doubt and the struggle to acknowledge one's own worth, while the raw and unrefined nature of the collection reflects the brutal reality of the human experience.

A hidden harmony beneath the surface represents the truth that we are all enough, just as we are. The collection invites the viewer to look within and acknowledge their own struggles and triumphs and to find comfort in the realization that the feeling of being enough is always present, like an echo that lingers. 

It is a reminder that we are enough, just as we are.



The artwork is fully created in javascript with the p5js library. 
The ideal viewing resolution is 1000x1000, and the artwork can be scaled to any size/resolution. The grain effect will fade slightly for higher resolutions.

metadata.name: Iteration is Usually Recursive (Pt. 1) #134
metadata.description:
This is the companion piece released with 'Iteration is Usually Recursive — Introduction: Finding answers in pre-computational art', the first in a series of essays, some long, some short, on generative art, theory and the practitioners of the medium. 

This piece started a simple experimen recreating George Nees’ Schotter (1968)— a classic piece of generative art history — as vanilla js SVG graphics. From there, I specifically developed it with non-plotter printing in mind, and more specific still, Riso Printing (think a scanner with a digital screen-printer MacGyver’d on). The palettes are taken from hex-estimated Risograph colour gamuts, with three layers being multiplied together to replicate, to some degree, the blending of the semi-transparent Risographic inks. Within this study, there’s a few different things going on, the initial setup is rectangles which cascade down the canvas, inheriting more extreme rotation as they get closer to the bottom (a la Schotter). The second is a subdivision of the shapes with filled circled, outlined circles and squares — since in this study the base shapes are rectangles and not squares, distribution of the ‘dithering’ can be larger than a single ‘pixel’ size — when these multiple layers overlap, the shapes produce a halftone-moire effect, forms and structures appear from the noise as the underlying patterns intersect. 

tx: Who?, Cosimo, Liam Egan, Andreas Rau, Louis

Licensing: CC-BY-NC-ND

metadata.name: The Artifact #78
metadata.description:
An archaeological artifact from the future, when many everyday objects are produced by generative algorithms. Some artifacts are in one piece, and others are fragmented. The color palettes are named after the rivers where artifacts in this design have first been discovered.

URL and interactive features:

- Append &r=<number> to the URL to change the image resolution. For example, &r=0.5 will halve the pixel count along both width and height, and &r=2 will double it.

- Append &d=<number> to the URL to change the pixel density. For example, &d=0.3 will generate a very quick, coarse render, and &d=2 will generate very fine stippling.

- Append &p to the URL to reveal detailed parameter settings used for the artwork.

- Append &h to the URL to suppress the notification that rendering is in progress.

- Press 's' in the live view to save the rendered image as a png.

The generative code is written in plain JavaScript. Polygon boundaries are determined via t-SNE, which is implemented in AssemblyScript and compiled to WebAssembly (WASM) for maximum performance. No external libraries have been used. Licensed CC0.

Author:
Claus O. Wilke
https://clauswilke.com/art
https://twitter.com/clauswilke

metadata.name: Lands #69
metadata.description:
Lands are a group of artworks creating a minimalist and abstract satellite view. The earth is changing, more and more, day after day, the satellite views are a great proof of that. Stay aware and be careful is important.

I wanted to representing something real, linked with my values, and keep a beautiful composition and colors harmony.  I worked with a new fresh touch for the colors management.

The size, position and frequency of the pieces are generated for each token, along with the color theme. 

Features : 
- piecesCount : the number of circles and rectangles.
- glitchLinesCount :  the number of lines behind the shapes.
- MultipleGlitchDirections : if the directions of the lines behind are just horizontal or vertical, or both (10% of chance to have only one direction) .

 Handmade by code with Javascript, made with fragment.tools
 Quentin Hocdé, Brussels (Belgium), 2023.

metadata.name: Slumbers #158
metadata.description:
Generative abstract artwork that explores forms, shapes, coloring and brushwork.

Options:

- press 'f' to turn off paper-like texture (recommended for print on hi-quality paper)
- press 's' to save the PNG image of the current view
- press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to save hi-res PNG images

Colors and textures might differ slightly on some devices due to the heavy use of low alpha blending. Calibrated and tested on Firefox 107.0 & Chrome 107.0.5304.107 on Win10 x64 Intel machine.

Created using p5js.

@VolatileMoods, November, 2022.

metadata.name: DIGITAL DISOBEDIENCE #113
metadata.description:
As artists, we believe it is our duty to use our skills to comment on the state of the world and the pressing issues facing humanity. Through our art, we aim to pre-empt the future and explore the potential consequences of our current actions. We use symmetry as a visual metaphor for the balance we must strive for in society, particularly in regards to human rights and the treatment of marginalized groups. In the age of technology and AI advancements, it is more important than ever to consider the impact these developments may have on our world and the diverse individuals and communities that inhabit it. Our work serves as a reminder that we must take responsibility for our actions and work towards creating a more just and equitable future for all.

This token is part of the Floor Exhibit co-curated by the NFT Museum of Newberry, SC and Fort Gallery NFT.

metadata.name: paintflow #189
metadata.description:
For this project, I wanted to try out Ty Vek's SVG technique for creating gen art. I used some basic SVG filters to achieve the paint brush effect, then just added some simple line and curve patterns. The result is quite nice and organic feeling! There are only 2 colors: red and black - I felt it was important to focus on the shapes and lines rather than the colors. The number of curves varies from 2 to 4, and each can be filled above or below. That's the gist of it! I hope you get some pretty pieces.

You can save the generated SVG by pressing the 's' key, and you can save a PNG version by pressing the 'p' key.

Please enjoy!

metadata.name: Set Disorder #238
metadata.description:
Set Disorder is a work of abstract art using only rectangles and line dashes as brushes, and layered color alpha values as paint. 

The shapes are arranged along a simple grid constrained within one of three aspect ratios; 3:4 / 1:1 / 4:3.

There are 12 color palettes, only one of them is monochrome. 👀 

Click or tap on the image to save a png.

made with p5js
@devgenart, 2022

metadata.name: Step by Step #118
metadata.description:
Step by Step explores the feeling of being stuck, confined - walking the path ahead of you often only seeing the immediate next step until exhaustion. We all feel this way from time to time — in our lives, jobs, bodies, situations — yet in our search for something, we shouldn't forget that there can still be beauty along the path.

The project takes some inspiration from Henri Matisse, both in the aesthetics of his later works (i.e. the "Cut Outs") and metaphorically in the sense that he had underwent medical treatment which left him wheelchair- or bed-bound towards the later part of his life, forcing him to give up painting, yet in his exploration of this new creative medium which involved cutting paper and pinning them up, his unorthodox work went on to become the most transformative of his career.

Released as part of the 4th edition of the Cure³ Parkinson's cure fundraiser exhibition organized by Artwise Curators and Bonhams as part of a specially comissioned selection of generative artists minting NFTs, curated by Foteini Valeonti and Alex Estorick with the support of fx(hash) at Bonhams, London from 13-17th January 2023.

---
33% of primary sales and 3% of secondary sales will be donated on-chain to Cure Parkinson’s
---

Controls:
• 'R' regenerates the piece (e.g. in case the window size changes)

Made in p5js
Created Jan 2023
